data.content:
## What happened

In C# 14 / .NET 10, new **span conversion rules** make `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(this ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` a better overload match than `Enumerable.Contains<T>(this IEnumerable<T>, T)` when the receiver is an array. Expression trees **cannot represent calls to span-based methods**, so the compiled expression throws at runtime.

## How to fix

Force the compiler to bind to `Enumerable.Contains` by making the receiver explicitly `IEnumerable<T>`:

```csharp
// Option 1: cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Any of these prevent the span overload from being selected and keep the expression tree representable.
